Description: PURPOSE: THE PRIMARY ACTIVITY OF THE RECIPIENT IS TO PROVIDE TECHNICAL SUPPORT IN THE APPLICATION OF PFHYDRO MODEL FOR THE TRANSPORT OF A SUITE OF WATER QUALITY CONTAMINANTS FOLLOWING FIRES. IN PARTICULAR, THE POST FIRE WATER QUALITY CONSTITUENTS NEED TO BE DEFINED AND ESTIMATED FOR THE WATERSHED BASED OF FIRE BEHAVIOR AND FUELS. ONCE THESE PARAMETERS ARE ESTABLISHED, THE RECIPIENT WILL HELP QUANTIFY THE INPUTS TO BE USED IN THE MODEL. ONCE A MODEL IS ESTABLISHED, THE RECIPIENT WILL HELP WITH VALIDATING THE MODEL AND ANALYZING THE MODEL RESULTS. INCREASED NUTRIENT AND METAL LOADING TO RESERVOIRS INCREASES THE OCCURRENCE OF ALGAL BLOOMS AND DEGRADES WATER QUALITY. BOTH CAN HAVE IMPACTS ON FISHERIES AND PUBLIC HEALTH. UNDERSTANDING THE EFFECTS OF FIRE WILL HELP WATER MANAGERS. ACTIVITIES TO BE PERFORMED:- TASK 1: LITERATURE REVIEW- TASK 2: SUPPORT OF MODELLING- TASK 3: DEVELOPMENT OF WATER QUALITY MODULE- TASK 4: PARTICIPATE IN ONGOING DISCUSSION AND DEVELOPMENT OF ANNUAL REPORT- TASK 5: DEVELOP PARAMETER SET FOR WATER QUALITY MODELLING- TASK 6: SUPPORT MODELLING AND PROVIDE ANALYSIS OF RESULTS- TASK 7: PARTICIPATE IN ONGOING DISCUSSION AND DEVELOPMENT OF FINAL REPORTEXPECTED OUTCOME(S): - REPORT 1: LITERATURE REVIEW- REPORT 2: CONCEPTUAL MODEL WITH PRELIMINARY GEOSPATIAL DATA- REPORT 3: FINAL REPORT AND PUBLICATIONBENEFICIARY: THE PUBLIC

R22AC00213 - REAL TIME WATER QUALITY MONITORING IN THE GRASSLAND RESOURCE CONSERVATION DISTRICT1. AWARD PURPOSE: THE PROJECT WILL ADDRESS SALINITY DISCHARGES FROM GRASSLAND RESOURCE CONSERVATION DISTRICT WETLANDS TO THE LOWER SAN JOAQUIN RIVER WATERSHED THAT INCLUDES IMPLEMENTATION OF MITIGATION ACTIONS FOR AREAS OF HIGH SALT ACCUMULATION SUCH AS WETLANDS AND AGRICULTURE DISCHARGES.2. ACTIVITIES TO BE PERFORMED: THIS PROJECT WILL MAINTAIN, UPDATE, ENHANCE AND EXPAND THE EXISTING WATER QUALITY AND FLOW MONITORING NETWORK WITHIN THE GRASSLAND RESOURCE CONSERVATION DISTRICT TO ALLOW FOR EFFICIENT AND ACCURATE DATA ACQUISITION, AS WELL AS IMPROVE AND INCREASE OPPORTUNITIES FOR RETURN FLOW REUSE.3. EXPECTED DELIVERABLES OR OUTCOMES: THE OBJECTIVE OF THIS AGREEMENT WILL PROVIDE DATA TO POPULATE THE WATERSHED MANAGEMENT FRAMEWORK (WARMF) MODEL, A COMPREHENSIVE DECISION SUPPORT TOOL DESIGNED TO FACILITATE TMDL DEVELOPMENT AT THE WATERSHED-LEVEL.4. INTENDED BENEFICIARIES: THIS PROJECT IS INTENDED TO MAKE THE REAL-TIME WATER QUALITY MANAGEMENT PROGRAM STRIVES TO MAKE 2-WEEK FORECASTS OF SALT LOAD ASSIMILATIVE CAPACITY AVAILABLE - SUFFICIENT TIME FOR AGRICULTURAL WATER DISTRICTS AND WETLAND ENTITIES TO TAKE NECESSARY ACTIONS TO ENSURE CONTINUED COMPLIANCE WITH SAN JOAQUIN RIVER SALINITY OBJECTIVES.5. SUBRECIPIENT ACTIVITIES (IF KNOWN OR SPECIFIED AT TIME OF AWARD): N/A
USING LICHENS AS A BIOINDICATOR OF ATMOSPHERIC MERCURY DISPOSITION TO RESERVOIRS IN CALIFORNIA
DELTA EDUCATION AND OUTREACH PROJECTS

THE PRIMARY OBJECTIVE OF THIS WORK IS TO DEVELOP A CONCEPTUAL MODEL FOR THE TRANSPORT OF NUTRIENTS FOLLOWING FIRES. IN PARTICULAR, THE EFFECTS OF PHOSPHATE-BASED FIRE RETARDANTS ON POST FIRE NUTRIENT LOADING TO DOWNSTREAM WATERBODIES WILL BE EXAMINED.  THE LEACHABLE FRACTIONS OF PHOSPHATE, AND PARTICULATE ASSOCIATE PHOSPHATE WILL BE EXAMINED BASED ON FIRE SEVERITY (HEATING AND DURATION) AND RETARDANT APPLICATION. RESULTS WILL BE INCORPORATED INTO A SPATIAL MODEL THAT CAN BE USED TO PREDICT WATERSHED-SCALE NUTRIENT LOADING FOLLOWING FIRE.

ANALYSIS CONDUCTED AS PART OF THIS COOPERATIVE ECOSYSTEM STUDIES UNITS (CESU) GRANT IN CONJUNCTION WITH RECLAMATION STAFF WILL HELP TO DETERMINE THE OVERALL IMPACT OF INDIVIDUAL GSPS ON THE RECLAMATION SERVICE AREA WITHIN THE SAN JOAQUIN RIVER BASIN BY COMBINING THESE INDIVIDUAL GSP MODELS INTO THE FRAMEWORK OF A REGIONAL SURFACE-GROUNDWATER SIMULATION MODEL AND COMPARING RESULTS WITH SIMULATION OUTPUTS FROM EXISTING PUBLISHED AND CALIBRATED DWR AND USGS MODELS.

THE PROJECT IS PART OF GHMWC'S COMPREHENSIVE PLAN FOR SYSTEM MODERNIZATION, BOUNDARY FLOW MONITORING, AND DEBRIS MANAGEMENT DEVELOPED AS PART OF THE 2014 FEATHER RIVER REGIONAL AGRICULTURAL WATER MANAGEMENT PLAN.  THE PROJECT CONSERVES WATER BY REDUCING OPERATIONAL SPILLAGE AND TAILWATER THROUGH A COMBINATION OF INFRASTRUCTURE IMPROVEMENTS AND IMPLEMENTATION OF REAL-TIME FLOW MONITORING AND DIVERSION CONTROL.

AS A BENEFIT TO THE PUBLIC, THE RECIPIENT WILL PROVIDE PUBLIC OUTREACH PROGRAMS, SUCH AS WATER TOURS, WORKSHOPS, CONFERENCES, LAYPERSON'S GUIDES ON WATER ISSUES, AND WESTERN WATER ARTICLES THAT PRESENT INFORMATION REGARDING: (1) IMPLEMENTATION OF PLANNING EFFORTS AIMED AT ENSURING SUSTAINABILITY, SUCH AS FLOODPLAIN RESTORATION, AND POLICY/SCIENTIFIC DISCUSSIONS ON DELTA CONVEYANCE  (2) CLIMATE CHANGE IMPACTS SPECIFIC TO THE DELTA, INCLUDING SEA-LEVEL RISE; 
(3) WATER QUALITY IMPACTS TO THE DELTA, INCLUDING STATE PLANS TO MITIGATE THOSE IMPACTS BY INCREASING FLOWS IN THE RIVERS IN THE DELTA WATERSHED AND HOW THOSE PLANS WOULD IMPACT THE FARMERS AND THE WATER DISTRICTS TO THE PUBLIC AT LARGE; (4) IMPORTANCE OF THE DELTA WATERSHED IN CALIFORNIA'S WATER PORTFOLIO AS WELL AS THE IMPORTANCE OF WATER CONSERVATION EFFORTS TO RELIEVE PRESSURE ON THE DELTA, THEREBY PROMOTING SUSTAINABILITY AND RESILIENCY OF THE DELTA AND ITS ENVIRONMENT AND, (5) SCIENTIFIC DISCOVERIES AND ANALYSIS ON THE DELTA WATERSHED TO BUILD PUBLIC KNOWLEDGE. 

THESE PROGRAMS ARE TARGETED TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC, AS WELL AS LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL OFFICIALS, TO EDUCATE AND PROVIDE MEANINGFUL COMMUNICATION ABOUT ACTIVITIES THAT AFFECT THE CALIFORNIA BAY-DELTA WATERSHED. THESE PUBLIC OUTREACH PROGRAMS ARE RELATED TO WATER SUPPLY RELIABILITY, WATER QUALITY AND ECOLOGICAL RESTORATION EFFORTS IN THE DELTA.
THESE OUTREACH EFFORTS ARE INTEGRAL BY HELPING THE PUBLIC UNDERSTAND THE PROCESS OF HOW RESOURCES ARE BEING PROTECTED AND TAX DOLLARS ARE BEING SPENT.
